Transactions on the Nigerian equities market closed negative yesterday by extending the downtrend to four consecutive trading sessions, amid sell pressure on Banking and Consumer Goods sector. The All-Share Index (ASI) decreased by 23.38 absolute points, representing a dip of 0.08 per cent to close at 27,547.56 points. Similarly, the overall market capitalisation size shed N13 billion to close at N14.347 trillion. The downturn was impacted by losses recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Guaranty Trust Bank, United Bank for Africa (UBA), FBN Holdings, Vitafoam Nigeria and Zenith Bank. Analysts at Afrinvest Limited said that “We maintain our bearish outlook on the equities market pending the corporate earnings release of tier-one Banking stocks. However, we note that there are opportunities for bargain hunting.” Also, Imperial Asset Managers Limited expected market to maintain prevailing trend in the next session amid safety precaution. However, bargain hunting activities are expected to be prominent. Consequently, the market breadth closed negative, recording 12 gainers against 13 losers. UACN Property Development Company and Wapic Insurance recorded the highest price gain of 10 per cent each, to close at 99 kobo and 33 kobo, respectively, while C & I Leasing followed with a gain 7.41 per cent to close at N5.80, per share. Neimeth International Pharmaceuticals went up by 6.67 per cent to close at 48 kobo, while Jaiz Bank rose by 4.41 per cent  to close at 71 kobo, per share. On the other hand, Law Union and Rock Insurance led the losers’ chart by 4.81 per cent, to close at 99 kobo, per share. Services followed with a decline of 4.76 per cent to close at 20 kobo, while Courteville Business Solutions shed 4.55 per cent to close at 21 kobo, per share.